04659nam a22007095i 9781442688490DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999360380  a97814426884907 a10.3138/97814426884902doi  a(DE-B1597)465391  a(OCoLC)944176669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ1073b.B394 2008eb 7aSOC0360002bisacsh04a306.91 aBayatrizi, Zohreh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife Sentences :bThe Modern Ordering of Mortality /cZohreh Bayatrizi. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Modern Ordering of Mortality -- t1. Thou Shalt Not Die Violently: Death and the Modern Problematic of Order -- t2. Thou Shalt Not Die Prematurely: The Political Economy of Death -- t3. Thou Shalt Not Kill Thyself: The De-moralization of Suicide -- t4. Thou Shalt Not Die an Undignified Death: The Discursive Constitution of Death with Dignity -- tConclusion: Thou Shalt Die an Orderly Death -- tReferences -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeath has popularly had the reputation of being the last of life's great mysteries, a subject of speculation, and as a foreboding event both inevitable, and feared. In Life Sentences, Zohreh Bayatrizi examines the many concerted attempts from the last 350 years to strip death of its mystery, and to order, manage, and transform it from an individualized and fatalistic event to a social phenomenon that allows intervention. She examines the process that has caused death to be understood in five quasi-biblical commandments: "thou shalt not die violently; thou shalt not die prematurely; thou shalt not kill thyself; and thou shalt not die an undignified death, so that thou shalt die an orderly death." Beginning with John Graunt's Natural and Political Observations Made upon the Bills of Mortality (1662) - considered the first book of statistics - and philosopher Thomas Hobbes's declaration that society must minimize the "greatest evil" of unsanctioned violent deaths, Bayatrizi traces the pivotal moments that have changed our understanding of death. While illuminating the history of our increasingly rationalized understanding of death, she also examines some of our most contradictory reactions to controversial topics such as suicide, euthanasia, suicide bombing, "collateral damage," and how our moral values have been shaped by an understanding of the proper place of a well-ordered death in modern society. Both historically rigorous and vigorously engaged in contemporary debates, Life Sentences will be of interest to anyone interested in how we deal with death before we die.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aDeathxSocial aspectszWestern countriesxHistory. 0aLife and death, Power overxSocial aspectsxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Death & Dying.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268849040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442688490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442688490.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK